postcontent:
S# 97805, 6.35 mm (25 auto), 3 inch barrel, bright excellent bore. This pistol was produced for only two or three years between 1914 and 1917 making it one of the less common variations of the 1910 based pocket automatics. This pistol is in excellent condition with 96% blue showing light holster wear on forward edges. Trigger shows beautiful fire blue, on takedown latch fire blue is worn on edges, bright in center. Grips show a tiny chip on each side with light wear. All numbers visible match serial number and a small crown over U proof is tamped on slide. Comes with two correct 9 round magazines and a period pigskin holster missing the closure button that has held this pistol for many years. A super example of this early Mauser pocket auto with extra mag, A very nice holster and scarce plastic grips. A scarcer piece for the Mauser pocket collector.

title: For Sale:  Heckler & Koch USP .40 S&W Compact
postcontent: The HK USP Compact is a small frame pistol capable of firing full power loads. Based on the full-size USP models, these handy pistols combine compact size with optimum effective shooting performance. USP Compacts are smaller and lighter than large frame USPs. The reduction in trigger reach and grip circumference increases concealability and enhances shooting ergonomics. Unlike some subcompact semiautomatic pistols that use a difficult to shoot "two-finger grip" frame, the USP Compact uses a narrow, full-hand grip frame with a choice of interchangeable extended or flush-fitting magazine floorplates. This makes the pistol easy to shoot without sacrificing concealability. Like their large frame predecessors, USP Compacts are designed with the demanding needs of the law enforcement and military shooters in mind. Using a modified linkless Browning-type action, the USP Compact is built to take the punishment of high-energy +P loads. To reduce the length of the slide and barrel on the USP Compact, the mechanical recoil reduction system found on large frame USPs has been replaced by a specially designed flat compression spring contained in the captive recoil spring assembly by a polymer absorber bushing. Service life is still engineered to exceed 20,000 rounds. Easy to shoot, simple to maintain; the USP Compact is a reliable, safe, accurate, and highly concealable pistol. title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington 1100 Home defense 12 Ga.
postcontent:
It's a pre-'68 Remington 1100 12 Ga. that I have been turning into a home defense gun, but with a 23" bbl and the original magazine cap and spring (both included), it could be used for most anything. These shotguns have a well earned reputation for being some of the most reliable semi-autos ever made, right out of the box; and this one is no exception. They "updated" the design 2 times but still sell the same model as it was designed 50 years ago. I have made some upgrades to it including: "Competition Master" loading gate(much easier reloads - original part comes with it as well), extended charging handle, blued magazine extension to match the finish (7+1 capacity), full length top rail (aluminum and VERY light - only weighs ounces and removes easily if you please), flip up BUIS (not that you would *need* them unless shooting slugs over long range, but they are sighted in and accurate), over-sized safety button, and custom industrial Velcro stock saddle that includes a removable 8-round holder and an extra 6-shot holder. I chose the full length rail as it was the most economical way (both money and weight wise) to have a top rail for a red dot as well as a rail towards the front for a light. The folding sights are essentially place-holders until I got around to mounting a red dot (the most recommended sight being the Bushnell TRS-25). If I had a machine shop I think I could get rich making extremely low profile rail mounted sights for shotguns! None exist. For that matter there are several other platforms that don't need the raised sight picture of the AR-15, to which basically all BUIS are made for. The original wood on the shotgun was in really good condition apart from one spot about 1/4" wide. It obviously has some handling marks from its years of use, but I took good pics of the worst of it. I decided to keep the wood on it, and it looks very cool with the old/new side by side. It is completely reliable with most every load I have tried; the ONLY exception being some cheap target loads that measured well over 3.5" shot and un-crimped (supposedly 2.75" rounds). They simply wouldn't fit out of the ejection port. The blued finish is in excellent shape. The previous owner attempted a gold foil inlay on the decorative carvings in the receiver, but it did not turn out perfect. Some areas are better than others. The bbl is 23.5" vent-ribbed and threaded for chokes. It dons a Colonial IC choke currently. I have a 25 round Allen bandoleer and 40 rounds of high brass 9-pellet 00 Buck to go with it. I've got just over $1000 in it with all the upgrades, mods, and ammo.

First pic shows storage damage.

WINCHESTER with NEW SIMMONS SCOPE.       *RARE:  WINCHESTER MODEL -77 SEMI AUTO .22LR RIFLE WITH SCOPE,  scope is 40mm, Brand New:    
This is a Rare Winchester tube-fed semi-auto .22 rifle. There are a few of these floating around, but not many. They made 210,000 Winchester model 77's in the 1950's and 60's, which is quite a few.. But only 10 percent of those were tube-fed...that's 21,000. This is one of those Tube-fed models. I saw one sell on GunBroker 2 weeks ago for $455.00, without a scope.
This one is in very good condition...very good, and it functions perfect in every way and has every modern feature. They stopped making the Model 77 in the 1960's.
It is grooved for mounting a scope. (same size groove that is on the Ruger 10/22 and all .22 rifles). It has fully adjustable iron sites also. The bolt is on the left side, which is one of the tell-tale model 77 characteristics. It functions flawless and looks great. It will shoot cheap bulk ammo as fast as you can pull the trigger without a hiccup. This is a collector's gun due to it's age and very good condition.. BUT, it is just as much an everyday shooter. It has hardly been shot and has a lifetime of use in front of it.  It looks and feels better than a Ruger. It is a Winchester, back when they were the best. It's not overly heavy and it lacks nothing that a brand new .22 rifle has. You don't feel like your holding an old outdated gun. Model number is 160694
